ent document the ways in which coalitions have been built among immigrants from different nations, and between immigrant and native born peoples. The essays examine the ways in which questions of immigrant rights engage broader issues of identity, including gender, race, and sexuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aConstitutional lawzUnited States. 0aEmigration and immigration lawzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigrantsxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aSocial integrationxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aStates. 4aUnited. 4aexamination. 4aimmigration. 4amovement. 4aprovocative. 4arights. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814739358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814739358.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK